[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### A4 - MEDIUM: Score Versioning Problem Acknowledged But Solution Underspecified
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Location:** "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section, first paragraph on score versioning
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Issue:** The recipe correctly identifies that model retraining invalidates historical score comparisons. It mentions two solutions: (a) re-score full history with new model, or (b) maintain version-specific percentile baselines. But it doesn't recommend one over the other or discuss the practical implications:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Option (a) requires storing all historical feature matrices (not just scores), which could be terabytes for a large population over multiple years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Option (b) means your trajectory computation must be version-aware, only comparing scores produced by the same model version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The recipe's pseudocode in Step 2 stores `model_version` with each score (good), but the trajectory computation in Step 3 doesn't filter by model_version when computing slopes. This means a model version change would produce a spurious spike or drop in the trajectory, potentially triggering false flags.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Suggested fix:** Add to Step 3 pseudocode a comment: "// IMPORTANT: Only compute slopes using scores from the same model version. // If model_version changed during the history window, either: // (a) re-score historical periods with the current model, or // (b) compute slope only from scores produced by the current model version, // accepting a shorter effective history window after each model update." Also add a brief recommendation in the "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section: "For most organizations, option (b) is more practical: after a model retrain, accept a reduced trajectory window until enough new-version scores accumulate. Design your minimum data point threshold (currently 3) to account for this reset."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### A5 - LOW: Cost Estimate Could Include Data Transfer Costs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Location:** Prerequisites table, "Cost Estimate" row
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Issue:** The cost estimate covers Glue DPU-hours, SageMaker batch transform, S3 storage, and DynamoDB writes. It doesn't mention data transfer costs for pulling source data (EHR extracts, claims feeds) into S3, or cross-AZ data transfer within the VPC. For most organizations, the source data ingestion cost (especially if pulling from on-premises systems via Direct Connect or VPN) is a significant portion of the total pipeline cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Suggested fix:** Add a note: "Cost estimate excludes data ingestion from source systems (EHR, claims). If source data is on-premises, factor in Direct Connect or VPN data transfer costs. For a 500K-member population with 18-24 months of history, initial data load may be 50-200 GB; incremental monthly loads are typically 5-20 GB."
